```json
{
  "global": "Diagnose batch effects in scRNA-seq PCA results and identify the appropriate visualization method for assessing cell-type populations.",
  "subtasks": [
    {
      "subtask": "Analyze the PCA scatter plot to characterize sample clustering",
      "atomics": [
        "Examine the spatial distribution of treated and untreated samples in PC1-PC2 space",
        "Identify sample groupings: (C1,C3), (T1,T3), (T4,T5,C6), (T2,C5,C6), (T6,C2,C4)",
        "Determine that samples cluster by patient ID rather than by treatment status"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Diagnose the source of sample separation as batch or patient effects",
      "atomics": [
        "Observe that treated (T) and untreated (C) samples are intermixed within patient groupings",
        "Recognize that samples of the same patient cluster together despite different treatments",
        "Conclude that inter-patient variation dominates over treatment-induced variation",
        "Identify this as batch effects or patient-specific biological effects"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Identify limitations of PCA for cell-type visualization",
      "atomics": [
        "Recognize that PCA is linear and captures global variance structure",
        "Understand that dominant batch effects obscure cell-type cluster structure",
        "Determine that fine-grained cell population heterogeneity is masked in PCA space"
      ]
    },
    {
      "subtask": "Select and justify appropriate non-linear visualization method",
      "atomics": [
        "Identify t-SNE as a standard method for scRNA-seq cell-type visualization",
        "Identify UMAP as an alternative that preserves both local and global structure",
        "Justify these methods: they preserve local neighborhood relationships to reveal cell-type clusters",
        "Optionally pair with unsupervised clustering (k-means, Louvain) to identify populations"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "global_atomics": [
    "Verify the selected visualization method reveals distinct cell populations despite batch effects",
    "Consider whether batch correction preprocessing is necessary before applying the visualization method"
  ],
  "gold_actions": {
    "global": "Apply t-SNE or UMAP non-linear dimensionality reduction to visualize and assess cell-type populations in the scRNA-seq data.",
    "subtasks": [
      {
        "subtask": "Analyze PCA clustering pattern",
        "atomics": [
          "Observe samples group as (C1,C3), (T1,T3), (T4,T5,C6), (T2,C5,C6), (T6,C2,C4) in PC1-PC2 space",
          "Confirm clustering is organized by patient number (1-6), not treatment label",
          "Verify treated and control samples are distributed across all patient groups"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Classify the separation as batch effects",
        "atomics": [
          "Determine patient-level clustering indicates batch effects or patient-specific variation",
          "Calculate that inter-patient variance >> treatment-induced variance",
          "Identify sources: patient genetics, sequencing batch, environmental factors"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Assess PCA inadequacy for cell-type discovery",
        "atomics": [
          "Determine top principal components capture batch variance, not cell-type variance",
          "Recognize linear projection obscures local cell-type structure",
          "Conclude alternative dimensionality reduction approach is needed"
        ]
      },
      {
        "subtask": "Apply t-SNE or UMAP for cell-type visualization",
        "atomics": [
          "Compute t-SNE embedding or UMAP embedding of the gene expression matrix",
          "Generate 2D scatter plot of cell coordinates from the embedding",
          "Color cells by unsupervised clustering assignment",
          "Visually assess cell-type populations and degree of heterogeneity within samples"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "global_atomics": [
      "Verify visualization reveals distinct, interpretable cell clusters",
      "Optionally apply batch correction (Harmony, ComBat, Seurat integration) to improve cell-type separation"
    ]
  }
}
```

FINAL ANSWER: t-SNE or UMAP (non-linear dimensionality reduction methods that preserve local structure to reveal cell-type populations); the PCA results suggest batch effects or patient effects.
